DTSTAMP:20260513T094205Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a guided walk of Beneath the Turning Sky\, led by Priya Chauhan\, one of the curators from the MAP Exhibitions team. This session explores key works from the exhibition\, unpacking the artistic practices\, material approaches\, and ideas that shape its narratives around ecology\, climate\, and our relationship with the natural world.\nThrough close looking and thoughtful discussion\, this session reveals the stories behind the artworks\, how they were made\, why they matter\, and the questions they pose about our place in the universe. It’s an invitation to slow down\, observe closely\, and discover new layers of meaning within the exhibition.\nThis event is part of International Museum Day programming.
DTEND:20260524T113000Z
DTSTART:20260524T103000Z
SUMMARY:Beneath the Turning Sky
UID:1277@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/beneath-the-turning-sky-5/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Untitled-design-3.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260513T094359Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a guided walk of the exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany\, and Empire by Breanne Coelho from the MAP Team.\nBetween the 17th and 20th centuries\, the Indian subcontinent was the site of extensive botanical surveys under colonial rule. Plant collection and classification were closely tied to imperial economic\, medical\, and political interests\, and botanical illustration played a central role in this project. \nBringing together a new and historically significant collection of botanical art from this period\, the exhibition draws on recent scholarship to recover the often uncredited identities and histories of the Indian artists who made them.
DTEND:20260531T111500Z
DTSTART:20260531T103000Z
SUMMARY:Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire
UID:1279@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/paper-gardens-art-botany-and-empire/
END:VEVENT
